00:00:18.710 --> 00:00:20.930
And the senses we are going to discuss

00:00:20.930 --> 00:00:23.530
are pain and pleasure.

00:00:23.530 --> 00:00:27.410
Pain and pleasure reflect two
opposite ends of a continuum,

00:00:27.410 --> 00:00:32.230
a continuum that involves
detection of things in our skin

00:00:32.230 --> 00:00:34.780
and the perception, the understanding

00:00:34.780 --> 00:00:37.310
of what those events are.

00:00:37.310 --> 00:00:40.490
Our skin is our largest sensory organ

00:00:40.490 --> 00:00:42.650
and our largest organ indeed.

00:00:42.650 --> 00:00:46.210
It is much larger than any of
the other organs in our body.

00:00:46.210 --> 00:00:48.360
And it's an odd organ
if you think about it,

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:50.200
it has so many functions.

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:52.197
It acts as a barrier between our organs

00:00:52.197 --> 00:00:54.230
and the outside world,

00:00:54.230 --> 00:00:57.210
it harbors neurons nerve
cells that allow us

00:00:57.210 --> 00:01:01.440
to detect things like
light touch, or temperature

00:01:01.440 --> 00:01:03.900
or pressure of various kinds.

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:06.890
And it's an organ that
we hang ornaments on.

00:01:06.890 --> 00:01:09.230
People put earrings in their ears.

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:13.330
People decorate their
skin with tattoos and inks

00:01:13.330 --> 00:01:14.760
and other things.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:17.940
And it's an organ that
allows us to experience

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:21.760
either great pain or great pleasure.

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:24.800
So it's a multifaceted organ and it's one

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:28.030
that our brain needs to make
sense of in a multifaceted way.

00:01:28.030 --> 00:01:29.596
So today we're going to discuss all that.

00:01:29.596 --> 00:01:34.550
And most importantly, how you
can experience more pleasure

00:01:34.550 --> 00:01:37.550
and less pain by
understanding these pathways.

00:01:37.550 --> 00:01:40.200
We will also discuss things you can do,

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:42.800
and if you wish things you can take

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:45.740
that will allow you to
experience more pleasure

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:47.210
and less pain in response

00:01:47.210 --> 00:01:50.010
to a variety of different experiences.

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:51.330
Before I go any further,

00:01:51.330 --> 00:01:54.810
I want to highlight a particularly
exciting area of science

00:01:54.810 --> 00:01:55.643
that relates to the skin and to sensing

00:01:55.643 --> 00:01:58.620
of pleasure and pain,

00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:02.040
but has everything to do with motivation.

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:05.570
Motivation is something that
many people struggle with,

00:02:05.570 --> 00:02:10.300
not everybody, but most
people experience dips

00:02:10.300 --> 00:02:12.460
and peaks in their motivation

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:14.370
even if they really want something.

00:02:14.370 --> 00:02:16.930
How should we think about
these changes in motivation?

00:02:16.930 --> 00:02:18.550
What do they reflect?

00:02:18.550 --> 00:02:22.360
Well at a very basic level,
they reflect fluctuations

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:26.240
changes in the levels of a
chemical called dopamine.

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:28.460
Most of us have heard of dopamine.

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:31.510
Dopamine is a neuromodulator
meaning it modulates

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:35.430
or changes the way that
neurons nerve cells work.

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:37.590
Most of us have heard that dopamine

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:39.840
is the molecule of pleasure.

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:41.900
However, that is incorrect.

00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:46.693
Dopamine is a molecule of
motivation and anticipation.

00:02:47.540 --> 00:02:49.770
To illustrate how dopamine works,

00:02:49.770 --> 00:02:52.220
I want to highlight
some very important work

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:54.430
largely carried out by the laboratory

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:56.400
of a guy named Wolfram Schultz.

00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:59.093
The Schultz Laboratory has done dozens

00:02:59.093 --> 00:03:03.100
of excellent experiments
on the dopamine system

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:04.770
and have identified something called

00:03:04.770 --> 00:03:07.380
reward prediction error.

00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:08.880
Although in some sense
you can think about it

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:12.110
as reward prediction variance.

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:14.500
Changes in the levels
of dopamine depending

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:16.960
on whether or not you expect a reward

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:18.710
and whether or not you get the reward.

00:03:18.710 --> 00:03:20.460
So I'm going to make this very simple.

00:03:21.980 --> 00:03:25.410
Dopamine is released
into the brain and body

00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:29.220
and generally makes us feel
activated and motivated,

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:32.410
as if we have energy to pursue a goal.

00:03:32.410 --> 00:03:34.830
And it is released into the brain and body

00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:37.420
in anticipation of a reward.

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:39.080
Measurements of dopamine have been made

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:40.480
in animals and humans.

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:44.920
And what you find is that
when we anticipate a reward,

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:46.680
dopamine is released,

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:49.330
we will put in the work
to achieve that reward.

00:03:49.330 --> 00:03:51.770
That work could be mental
work or physical work,

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:54.490
but when the reward arrives,

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:57.350
dopamine levels drop
back down to baseline.

00:03:57.350 --> 00:03:58.183
That's right.

00:03:58.183 --> 00:03:59.230
When we receive a reward,

00:03:59.230 --> 00:04:02.500
dopamine levels go back down to baseline.

00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:05.190
So the way to envision this
as you can just imagine

00:04:05.190 --> 00:04:08.040
a sort of increase in dopamine
as we anticipate something

00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:10.690
we're working towards it,
we're working towards a goal.

00:04:10.690 --> 00:04:13.480
We're excited about seeing
somebody or meeting somebody

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:16.580
or receiving some reward
and then the reward comes

00:04:16.580 --> 00:04:18.570
and dopamine goes down.

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:20.063
Now that's all fine and good,

00:04:20.910 --> 00:04:23.450
but there is a way to
get much more dopamine

00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:26.340
out of that process and therefore a way

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:29.310
to have much more
motivation, energy, and focus

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:33.420
because those are the
consequences of elevated dopamine.

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:38.040
The way to do that is to
not deliver the reward

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:40.120
on an expected schedule.

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:43.610
So experiments have been done
where there's an anticipation

00:04:43.610 --> 00:04:45.160
of a reward, there's work,

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:47.970
and then the reward
only arrives every other

00:04:47.970 --> 00:04:50.324
or every third about of work, okay?

00:04:50.324 --> 00:04:53.630
So this would be like
getting a pat on the head.

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:56.970
If you're a dog or a,
perhaps a child or an adult,

00:04:56.970 --> 00:05:00.950
or getting a monetary reward
only for every third project

00:05:00.950 --> 00:05:03.550
or every third race that you win.

00:05:03.550 --> 00:05:04.810
Pick any kind of goal.

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:05.643
It doesn't matter.

00:05:05.643 --> 00:05:07.630
These molecules don't care
about what you're pursuing.

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:11.760
They are a common currency of
different types of activities.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:14.190
That's a regular reward schedule,

00:05:14.190 --> 00:05:16.727
and it will not alter the
pattern of dopamine release

00:05:16.727 --> 00:05:18.700
that I described before.

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:23.460
However, if the reward
arrives intermittently

00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:27.340
almost randomly, so
you anticipate a reward

00:05:27.340 --> 00:05:29.740
as a maybe it might come, it might come.

00:05:29.740 --> 00:05:32.940
Then you work, work, work,
work, work, no reward.

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:35.270
You repeat the work, work,
work, work, work, work,

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:36.310
and then you get a reward.

00:05:36.310 --> 00:05:38.620
So some trials, you do
some trials, you don't,

00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:41.190
and it's completely random.

00:05:41.190 --> 00:05:43.670
Under those conditions, the amplitude,

00:05:43.670 --> 00:05:46.560
the amount of dopamine that's
released into your system

00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:49.890
and the motivation to
continue working hard

00:05:49.890 --> 00:05:52.500
or playing whatever kind
of game you're playing,

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:54.180
doubles or triples.

00:05:54.180 --> 00:05:56.330
And this is the basis of
things like slot machines

00:05:56.330 --> 00:05:57.163
and gambling.

00:05:57.163 --> 00:05:59.680
And this is why so many
people will give so much

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:04.680
of their money up to casinos
and the casinos always win.

00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:07.670
Sometimes people walk away with more money

00:06:07.670 --> 00:06:09.400
than they came to the casino with,

00:06:09.400 --> 00:06:11.750
but the vast majority of the time,

00:06:11.750 --> 00:06:13.570
the house wins as they say.

00:06:13.570 --> 00:06:15.130
And it's because they understand

00:06:15.130 --> 00:06:16.610
intermittent reward schedules.

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:19.080
And you can apply this to stay motivated

00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:21.120
in your own pursuits.

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:24.500
Rather than thinking about
the pleasure of a reward,

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:28.130
understand that dopamine
is released in response

00:06:28.130 --> 00:06:33.130
to anticipation reward, and
that is the fuel for work.

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:38.010
And every once in awhile at
random remove the reward.

00:06:38.010 --> 00:06:40.100
That's the way to continue
to stay motivated.

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:43.500
Not to reward every action or every goal.

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:44.500
And this is also true,

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:48.700
if you're trying to train up
children or train up players

00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:52.280
on a team, you should
not celebrate every win.

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:53.920
I know that's a little counter-intuitive,

00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:57.730
we're going to go more into
the biology of dopamine

00:06:57.730 --> 00:06:59.680
and how it relates to the pleasure system

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:01.150
later on in the podcast,

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:05.080
but for now understand
intermittent reward schedules

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:08.840
harness the biology of dopamine
in ways that can allow you

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:12.490
