01:01:55.740 --> 01:01:56.590
what's going on.

01:01:56.590 --> 01:01:58.970
A syndrome is a constellation of symptoms

01:02:00.030 --> 01:02:02.220
that point in a particular direction

01:02:02.220 --> 01:02:04.050
or some general set of directions about

01:02:04.050 --> 01:02:05.530
what could be going on,

01:02:05.530 --> 01:02:10.530
but it doesn't reveal a true
underlying disease necessarily.

01:02:10.580 --> 01:02:12.890
It could be aggregative diseases

01:02:12.890 --> 01:02:15.360
or it could be something else entirely.

01:02:15.360 --> 01:02:18.700
And I want to make sure that I emphasize

01:02:18.700 --> 01:02:21.400
the so-called psychosomatic phenomenon.

01:02:21.400 --> 01:02:23.590
I think sometimes we hear psychosomatic

01:02:23.590 --> 01:02:26.620
and we interpret that as
meaning all in one's head.

01:02:26.620 --> 01:02:28.410
But I think it's important to remember

01:02:28.410 --> 01:02:29.600
that everything is neural,

01:02:29.600 --> 01:02:31.410
whether that's pain in your body

01:02:31.410 --> 01:02:33.670
'cause you have a gaping wound

01:02:33.670 --> 01:02:35.620
and you're hemorrhaging out of that wound

01:02:35.620 --> 01:02:40.150
or whether or not it's pain
for which you cannot explain it

01:02:40.150 --> 01:02:41.640
on the basis of any kind of injury.

01:02:41.640 --> 01:02:42.680
It's all neural.

01:02:42.680 --> 01:02:46.033
So saying body, brain, or psychosomatic

01:02:46.033 --> 01:02:47.360
it's kind of irrelevant.

01:02:47.360 --> 01:02:49.713
And I hope someday we
move past that language.

01:02:51.120 --> 01:02:53.123
Psychosomatic is interesting.

01:02:54.760 --> 01:02:57.220
There was a paper that
was published in 2015,

01:02:57.220 --> 01:03:00.520
and then again in 2020 a different paper

01:03:00.520 --> 01:03:03.810
focused on the so-called
psychogenic fevers

01:03:03.810 --> 01:03:05.030
or psychosomatic effects.

01:03:05.030 --> 01:03:06.420
I just briefly want to mention this

01:03:06.420 --> 01:03:08.693
because it relates back to pain.

01:03:09.960 --> 01:03:11.790
These studies have shown
that there are areas

01:03:11.790 --> 01:03:13.050
of the so-called thalamus,

01:03:13.050 --> 01:03:15.770
which integrates and
filter sensory information

01:03:15.770 --> 01:03:17.250
of different kinds.

01:03:17.250 --> 01:03:20.287
And within the brainstem,
an area called the DMH

01:03:21.343 --> 01:03:24.060
and I can also provide a link
to this study if you like,

01:03:24.060 --> 01:03:28.110
that shows that there is
a true neurological basis.

01:03:28.110 --> 01:03:31.110
There are brain areas and
circuits that are related to

01:03:31.110 --> 01:03:34.430
what's called psychogenic
fever when we are stressed.

01:03:34.430 --> 01:03:37.620
And in particular, if we
think that we were injured

01:03:37.620 --> 01:03:39.820
or that we were infected by something,

01:03:39.820 --> 01:03:43.090
we can actually generate a true fever.

01:03:43.090 --> 01:03:45.240
It is not an imagined fever.

01:03:45.240 --> 01:03:48.320
It is our thinking generating

01:03:48.320 --> 01:03:50.510
an increase in body temperature.

01:03:50.510 --> 01:03:52.630
And so this has been called psychosomatic.

01:03:52.630 --> 01:03:56.790
It's been called psychogenic,
but it has a neural basis.

01:03:56.790 --> 01:04:01.460
So when we hear syndrome and
a patient comes into a clinic

01:04:01.460 --> 01:04:03.690
and says that they suffer for instance,

01:04:03.690 --> 01:04:06.150
from something which is
very controversial frankly

01:04:06.150 --> 01:04:07.750
like chronic fatigue syndrome,

01:04:07.750 --> 01:04:10.050
some physicians believe that it reflects

01:04:10.050 --> 01:04:13.438
a real underlying medical
condition, others don't.

01:04:13.438 --> 01:04:18.220
However, syndrome means
we don't understand.

01:04:18.220 --> 01:04:21.290
And that doesn't mean
something doesn't exist.

01:04:21.290 --> 01:04:25.320
Fibromyalgia or whole
body pain for a long time

01:04:25.320 --> 01:04:28.630
was written off or kind of explained away

01:04:28.630 --> 01:04:32.290
by physicians and scientists
frankly, my community

01:04:32.290 --> 01:04:34.370
as one of these syndromes.

01:04:34.370 --> 01:04:35.520
It couldn't be explained.

01:04:35.520 --> 01:04:38.760
However, now there is
what I would consider

01:04:38.760 --> 01:04:41.880
and I think others would
and should consider

01:04:41.880 --> 01:04:45.110
from understanding of at
least one of the bases

01:04:45.110 --> 01:04:46.920
for this whole body pain.

01:04:46.920 --> 01:04:50.240
And that's activation of
a particular cell type

01:04:50.240 --> 01:04:51.880
called glial.

01:04:51.880 --> 01:04:53.780
And there's a receptor on these glial

01:04:53.780 --> 01:04:57.100
for those of you that want to
know called the toll 4 receptor

01:04:57.100 --> 01:05:01.000
and activation of the
toll 4 receptor is related

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:04.970
to certain forms of whole
body pain and fibromyalgia.

01:05:04.970 --> 01:05:08.470
Now, what treatments
exist for fibromyalgia.

01:05:08.470 --> 01:05:10.290
And even if you don't
suffer from fibromyalgia,

01:05:10.290 --> 01:05:13.200
and even if you don't know anyone who does

01:05:13.200 --> 01:05:14.480
this is important information

01:05:14.480 --> 01:05:16.290
because what I'm about to tell you relate

01:05:16.290 --> 01:05:20.800
to how you and your body,
which is you of course

01:05:20.800 --> 01:05:23.100
can deal with pain of any kind.

01:05:23.100 --> 01:05:26.560
And there are actually things
that one can do and take

01:05:26.560 --> 01:05:29.560
that can encourage
nerve health in general.

01:05:29.560 --> 01:05:31.770
In other conditions like
diabetic neuropathy,

01:05:31.770 --> 01:05:34.140
but in all individuals.

01:05:34.140 --> 01:05:39.140
So there are clinical data
using a prescription drug.

01:05:40.290 --> 01:05:41.570
This is work that actually was done

01:05:41.570 --> 01:05:43.940
by Dr. Mackey and colleagues.

01:05:43.940 --> 01:05:44.890
The drug is called naltrexone.

01:05:44.890 --> 01:05:47.520
Naltrexone is actually
used for the treatment

01:05:47.520 --> 01:05:51.780
of various opioid addictions
and things of that sort,

01:05:51.780 --> 01:05:54.080
but it turns out that a very low dose,

01:05:54.080 --> 01:05:58.810
I believe it was a one 10th
the size of the typical dose

01:05:58.810 --> 01:06:03.415
of naltrexone has been
shown to have some success

01:06:03.415 --> 01:06:06.650
in dealing with and treating
certain forms of fibromyalgia.

01:06:06.650 --> 01:06:09.520
And it has that success
because of its ability

01:06:09.520 --> 01:06:14.360
to bind to and block these
toll four receptors on glial.

01:06:14.360 --> 01:06:17.250
So this so-called syndrome
or this thing that previously

01:06:17.250 --> 01:06:19.120
was called a syndrome, fibromyalgia

01:06:19.120 --> 01:06:21.230
actually has a biological basis.

01:06:21.230 --> 01:06:23.660
It was not just inpatients heads.

01:06:23.660 --> 01:06:26.630
And I really tip my hat to
the medical establishment

01:06:26.630 --> 01:06:28.470
including Dr. Mackey and others

01:06:28.470 --> 01:06:32.070
who explored the potential
underlying biologies

01:06:32.070 --> 01:06:33.810
of things like fibromyalgia
and are starting

01:06:33.810 --> 01:06:35.030
to arrive at treatments.

01:06:35.030 --> 01:06:37.070
Now, I'm not a physician, I'm a professor,

01:06:37.070 --> 01:06:38.590
so I'm not prescribing anything.

01:06:38.590 --> 01:06:39.970
You should talk to your doctor of course,

01:06:39.970 --> 01:06:43.170
if you have fibromyalgia
or other forms of chronic

01:06:43.170 --> 01:06:46.100
or whole body pain to explore
whether or not these low dose

01:06:46.100 --> 01:06:48.860
naltrexone treatments are right for you.

01:06:48.860 --> 01:06:51.640
But I think it's a beautiful
case study if you will,

01:06:51.640 --> 01:06:53.340
not a case study of an individual patient,

01:06:53.340 --> 01:06:58.340
but a case in study of linking
up the patient's self-report

01:06:58.340 --> 01:07:00.790
of these experiences and using science

01:07:00.790 --> 01:07:03.500
to try to establish clinical treatments.

01:07:03.500 --> 01:07:05.280
There's another treatment,

01:07:05.280 --> 01:07:06.920
or I should say there's another approach

01:07:06.920 --> 01:07:07.753
that one could take.

01:07:07.753 --> 01:07:10.220
And again, I'm not recommending
people do this necessarily.

01:07:10.220 --> 01:07:12.310
You have to determine what's
right and say for you,

01:07:12.310 --> 01:07:13.510
I cannot do that.

01:07:13.510 --> 01:07:15.790
There's no way your
situation's very far too much,

01:07:15.790 --> 01:07:18.300
and it would be outside of my wheelhouse

01:07:18.300 --> 01:07:22.850
to prescribe anything, but
there's a particular compound

01:07:22.850 --> 01:07:25.190
which in the United States
is sold over the counter

01:07:25.190 --> 01:07:26.730
and in Europe is prescription.

01:07:26.730 --> 01:07:28.970
It's one that I've talked
about on this podcast before

01:07:28.970 --> 01:07:30.110
for other purposes.

01:07:30.110 --> 01:07:33.437
And that compound is acetylcarnitine.

01:07:34.309 --> 01:07:36.947
Acetylcarnitine as I
mentioned is by prescription

01:07:36.947 --> 01:07:38.317
in most countries in Europe

01:07:38.317 --> 01:07:41.250
and the US you can buy
this over the counter.

01:07:41.250 --> 01:07:44.980
There is evidence that
acetylcarnitine can reduce

01:07:44.980 --> 01:07:46.930
the symptoms of chronic whole body pain

01:07:46.930 --> 01:07:49.650
and other certain forms of acute pain

01:07:49.650 --> 01:07:53.160
at dosages of somewhere
between one to three

01:07:53.160 --> 01:07:55.480
and sometimes four grams per day.

01:07:55.480 --> 01:07:58.040
Now acetylcarnitine can be taken orally.

01:07:58.040 --> 01:08:00.770
It's found in 500 milligram capsules,

01:08:00.770 --> 01:08:03.290
as well as by injection.

01:08:03.290 --> 01:08:06.660
By injection in the States
in the United States that is

01:08:06.660 --> 01:08:08.350
also requires a prescription

01:08:08.350 --> 01:08:10.950
or requires a prescription I should say.

01:08:10.950 --> 01:08:13.260
The over-the-counter forms
are generally capsules

01:08:13.260 --> 01:08:14.540
or powders.

01:08:14.540 --> 01:08:17.610
Those apparently do not
require a prescription.

01:08:17.610 --> 01:08:20.500
There are several studies
exploring acetylcarnitine

01:08:20.500 --> 01:08:24.000
in this context, as well
as for diabetic neuropathy.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:26.330
And what's interesting about
acetylcarnitine is it's one

01:08:26.330 --> 01:08:30.070
of the few compounds that isn't just used

01:08:30.070 --> 01:08:31.650
for the treatment of pain,

01:08:31.650 --> 01:08:34.220
but has also been shown
in certain contacts

01:08:34.220 --> 01:08:37.800
to improve peripheral
nerve health generally.

01:08:37.800 --> 01:08:40.510
And for that reason, it's
an interesting compound.

01:08:40.510 --> 01:08:43.680
I've also talked about
acetylcarnitine on here previously,

01:08:43.680 --> 01:08:48.030
because it has robust effects
on things like spur motility

01:08:48.030 --> 01:08:52.960
and health, including the
speeds at which sperms swim,

01:08:52.960 --> 01:08:55.620
how straight they swim
turns out that swimming

01:08:55.620 --> 01:08:58.570
for sperm is more efficient
if they swim straight,

01:08:58.570 --> 01:09:02.450
as opposed to like those
kids in on the swim team,

01:09:02.450 --> 01:09:04.120
they're like banging up
against the lane lines

01:09:04.120 --> 01:09:06.230
and zigzagging all over the place.

01:09:06.230 --> 01:09:10.720
So it does turn out to be the
case that the quickest route

01:09:10.720 --> 01:09:12.619
between any two places is a straight line

01:09:12.619 --> 01:09:14.470
and the good sperm know that,

01:09:14.470 --> 01:09:16.707
and the less good sperm
don't seem to know that.

01:09:16.707 --> 01:09:19.850
And acetylcarnitine seems to
facilitate straight swimming

01:09:19.850 --> 01:09:21.640
trajectories as well as speed of swimming

01:09:21.640 --> 01:09:23.170
and overall sperm health.

01:09:23.170 --> 01:09:26.800
And there is evidence from
quality peer reviewed studies

01:09:26.800 --> 01:09:29.960
showing that acetylcarnitine
supplementation can also be

01:09:29.960 --> 01:09:33.840
beneficial for women's fertility
in ways that it affects

01:09:33.840 --> 01:09:36.610
perhaps we don't really
know the mechanism,

01:09:36.610 --> 01:09:39.800
health and status of the
egg or egg implantation.

01:09:39.800 --> 01:09:42.210
There are a large number of
studies on acetylcarnitine.

01:09:42.210 --> 01:09:44.700
You can look those up
on Pub Med, if you like,

01:09:44.700 --> 01:09:46.710
or on examine.com.

01:09:46.710 --> 01:09:48.500
There are some studies that I don't think

01:09:48.500 --> 01:09:50.410
are included there which are
particularly interesting.

01:09:50.410 --> 01:09:55.210
One that I just would like
to reference the last name

01:09:55.210 --> 01:10:00.210
of the first author is
Mahdavi M-A-H-D-A-V-I.

01:10:01.290 --> 01:10:02.580
The title of the paper is

01:10:02.580 --> 01:10:04.820
Effects of l -Carnitine Supplementation

01:10:04.820 --> 01:10:07.060
on Serum Inflammatory Markers

01:10:07.060 --> 01:10:09.780
and Matrix Metalloproteinases Enzymes

01:10:09.780 --> 01:10:12.130
in Females with Knee Osteoarthritis.

01:10:12.130 --> 01:10:14.630
So this is a randomized double
blind placebo controlled

01:10:14.630 --> 01:10:17.362
pilot study that showed
really interesting effects

01:10:17.362 --> 01:10:21.450
of short term supplementation
of acetylcarnitine.

01:10:21.450 --> 01:10:23.941
Longer term, the effects
were less impressive.

01:10:23.941 --> 01:10:26.360
So it's pretty interesting
that this compound has

01:10:26.360 --> 01:10:27.240
so many different effects.

01:10:27.240 --> 01:10:28.370
How could it have these effects?

01:10:28.370 --> 01:10:30.410
Well, it appears that
it's having these effects

01:10:30.410 --> 01:10:35.070
through its impact on the
so-called inflammatory cytokines.

01:10:35.070 --> 01:10:37.708
Inflammatory cytokines for
those of you that don't know

01:10:37.708 --> 01:10:39.760
are secreted by the immune system

01:10:39.760 --> 01:10:42.080
in response to different stressors,

01:10:42.080 --> 01:10:44.710
physical stressors, mental stressors too

01:10:44.710 --> 01:10:47.770
food that you eat that isn't good for you.

01:10:47.770 --> 01:10:49.210
The so-called hidden sugars.

01:10:49.210 --> 01:10:51.800
Yes, will increase inflammation

01:10:51.800 --> 01:10:53.150
if they're ingested too often,

01:10:53.150 --> 01:10:55.730
or in amounts that are
too high in quantity.

01:10:55.730 --> 01:10:57.940
Things like Interleukin 1 beta,

01:10:57.940 --> 01:10:59.730
things like C-reactive protein,

01:10:59.730 --> 01:11:01.230
things like interleukin 6.

01:11:01.230 --> 01:11:04.260
Interleukin 6 is kind of the
generic inflammatory marker

01:11:04.260 --> 01:11:05.490
that all studies refer to.

01:11:05.490 --> 01:11:07.490
And yet there are other interleukins,

01:11:07.490 --> 01:11:09.920
please note that there
are other interleukins

01:11:09.920 --> 01:11:13.720
like interleukin 10 that
are anti-inflammatory.

01:11:13.720 --> 01:11:16.520
So immune system can secrete
inflammatory molecules

01:11:16.520 --> 01:11:18.730
to deal with wounds and stress and things.

01:11:18.730 --> 01:11:19.960
And in the short term that's good,

01:11:19.960 --> 01:11:21.650
and in the longterm that's bad.

01:11:21.650 --> 01:11:26.650
And it can secrete anti-inflammatory
cytokines like IL10.

01:11:27.370 --> 01:11:29.490
And these matrix metalloproteinases,

01:11:29.490 --> 01:11:30.700
it's kind of a mouthful,

01:11:30.700 --> 01:11:33.030
but these matrix metalloproteinases
are very interesting.

01:11:33.030 --> 01:11:37.400
Anytime you see A-S-E, ASE
that's generally an enzyme,

01:11:37.400 --> 01:11:40.880
which means that these
compounds in this case,

01:11:40.880 --> 01:11:42.930
these matrix metalloproteinases are used

01:11:42.930 --> 01:11:46.994
to break down certain
elements around wounds

01:11:46.994 --> 01:11:49.820
and scoring which might
sound like a bad thing,

01:11:49.820 --> 01:11:53.170
but in some cases is good
because it allows certain cells

01:11:53.170 --> 01:11:55.130
like glial cells so-called microglia

01:11:55.130 --> 01:11:56.560
to come in like low ambulances,

01:11:56.560 --> 01:11:59.400
like low paramedics and clean up wounds.

01:11:59.400 --> 01:12:00.950
So scarring and inflammation

01:12:00.950 --> 01:12:02.640
is kind of a double-edged sword.

01:12:02.640 --> 01:12:05.130
It can be good, but too much scarring.

01:12:05.130 --> 01:12:06.870
If it contains a wound too much,

01:12:06.870 --> 01:12:09.030
doesn't allow the
infiltration of cell types

01:12:09.030 --> 01:12:11.750
to move in and take care of
that wound and heal it up.

01:12:11.750 --> 01:12:14.259
So it appears that L-carnitine
is impacting a number

01:12:14.259 --> 01:12:17.080
of different processes,
both to impact pain

01:12:17.080 --> 01:12:19.210
and perhaps, and I want
to underscore perhaps,

01:12:19.210 --> 01:12:21.260
but there are good studies happening now,

01:12:22.150 --> 01:12:25.660
perhaps accelerate wound healing as well.

01:12:25.660 --> 01:12:27.277
As long as we're talking about acute pain

01:12:27.277 --> 01:12:29.350
and chronic pain and supplementation

01:12:29.350 --> 01:12:32.060
and non-prescription drugs,
at least in the United States

01:12:32.060 --> 01:12:34.980
that people can take to deal
with pain of various kinds,

01:12:34.980 --> 01:12:36.920
I'd be remiss if I didn't mention the two

01:12:36.920 --> 01:12:39.010
that I get asked most often about,

01:12:39.010 --> 01:12:44.010
which are agmatine and
S-adenosyl-L-methionine,

01:12:44.207 --> 01:12:45.793
which is sometimes called SAMe.

01:12:47.010 --> 01:12:50.300
Both of those have been
shown to have some impact

01:12:51.420 --> 01:12:54.520
categorized on examine as notable impact

01:12:54.520 --> 01:12:58.190
on various forms of pain,
due to osteoarthritis,

01:12:58.190 --> 01:13:01.830
or due to injury of various
kinds of indifferent subject

01:13:01.830 --> 01:13:05.350
population, men, women, people
of different ages, et cetera.

01:13:05.350 --> 01:13:07.700
SAMe in particular has been interesting

01:13:07.700 --> 01:13:10.120
because it's been shown head to head

01:13:10.120 --> 01:13:14.350
with drugs like Naproxen and
other drugs of that sort,

01:13:14.350 --> 01:13:17.850
which are well established
and sold over the counter

01:13:17.850 --> 01:13:21.010
in the US to work at least as well

01:13:21.010 --> 01:13:24.030
as some of those compounds
at certain doses.

01:13:24.030 --> 01:13:26.847
But it's also shown that SAMe

01:13:26.847 --> 01:13:29.260
and some of those things take more time

01:13:29.260 --> 01:13:31.540
in order to have those effects.

01:13:31.540 --> 01:13:34.283
In fact, head to head
with things like Neproxin

01:13:34.283 --> 01:13:37.090
have been shown that they
can take up to a month

01:13:37.090 --> 01:13:39.300
in order to have the
pain relieving effect.

01:13:39.300 --> 01:13:40.990
Now, whether or not that
makes them a better choice

01:13:40.990 --> 01:13:43.640
or a worst choice really
depends on your circumstances.

01:13:43.640 --> 01:13:46.340
I'm certainly not recommending
that anybody take anything,

01:13:46.340 --> 01:13:48.930
but I do think it's interesting
and important to point out

01:13:48.930 --> 01:13:51.400
that things like
agmatine, things like SAMe

01:13:51.400 --> 01:13:53.629
have been shown under
certain circumstances

01:13:53.629 --> 01:13:57.020
to be beneficial for pain and
they are outside the realm

01:13:57.020 --> 01:13:58.030
of prescription drugs.

01:13:58.030 --> 01:14:00.260
I think this is a growing area of

01:14:00.260 --> 01:14:01.340
some people call them supplements,

01:14:01.340 --> 01:14:03.510
some people call them nutraceuticals.

01:14:03.510 --> 01:14:05.410
Look, at the end of the
day these are compounds

01:14:05.410 --> 01:14:06.960
that affect cellular processes.

01:14:06.960 --> 01:14:07.930
And the more that we understand

01:14:07.930 --> 01:14:09.658
how they affect those cellar processes

01:14:09.658 --> 01:14:13.110
as we now do for things
like acetylcarnitine,

01:14:13.110 --> 01:14:15.460
I think the more trust
that we can put into them,

01:14:15.460 --> 01:14:19.140
or the more to which we
might want to avoid them

01:14:19.140 --> 01:14:20.750
because of some of the side effects

01:14:20.750 --> 01:14:23.360
or contra-indications that
those compounds could have.

01:14:23.360 --> 01:14:25.408
If you're interested in
those other compounds,

01:14:25.408 --> 01:14:28.810
I do invite you as I always
do to check out examine.com,

01:14:28.810 --> 01:14:31.098
but also to do your
research on those compounds

01:14:31.098 --> 01:14:33.060
by simply putting them into Google

01:14:33.060 --> 01:14:35.390
or putting them into PubMed,
which would be even better.

01:14:35.390 --> 01:14:37.220
And if you are going to go into PubMed,

01:14:37.220 --> 01:14:39.160
if you're going to
start playing scientist,

01:14:39.160 --> 01:14:40.958
which I do encourage you to do,

01:14:40.958 --> 01:14:43.630
I would encourage you to
not just read abstracts,

01:14:43.630 --> 01:14:45.860
but if you can, if the
studies are freely available,

01:14:45.860 --> 01:14:48.080
I realized not all of
them are freely available

01:14:48.080 --> 01:14:49.260
to try and read those studies

01:14:49.260 --> 01:14:51.710
at least to the extent that you can.

01:14:51.710 --> 01:14:54.050
There's a particularly nice
study that you might look at

01:14:54.050 --> 01:14:57.460
that was published in
2010 in Pain Medicine,

01:14:57.460 --> 01:15:01.470
which is Keynan et al K-E-Y-N-A-N,

01:15:01.470 --> 01:15:03.340
which looked at the safety and efficacy

01:15:03.340 --> 01:15:05.510
of dietary agmatine sulfate

01:15:05.510 --> 01:15:08.807
on lumbar disc associated radiculopathy

01:15:11.660 --> 01:15:12.910
not laughing at the condition.

01:15:12.910 --> 01:15:16.900
It's a painful condition that describes a,

01:15:16.900 --> 01:15:18.910
it's a kind of a range
of symptoms that relate

01:15:18.910 --> 01:15:20.180
to pinching of nerves.

01:15:20.180 --> 01:15:21.013
The spinal columns,

01:15:21.013 --> 01:15:23.150
I was laughing at my pronunciation of it.

01:15:23.150 --> 01:15:25.570
That particular study is quite good.

01:15:25.570 --> 01:15:29.610
And the conclusion of that
study that they drew was that

01:15:29.610 --> 01:15:31.560
there were limited side effects

01:15:31.560 --> 01:15:34.240
and that dietary agmatine sulfate is safe

01:15:34.240 --> 01:15:36.670
and efficacious for treating
and alleviating pain

01:15:36.670 --> 01:15:38.470
and improving quality of life

01:15:38.470 --> 01:15:40.890
and lumbar-disc associated pain.

01:15:40.890 --> 01:15:45.890
However, there were very
specific dosage regimens

01:15:45.990 --> 01:15:48.250
that were described there
and duration of treatment.

01:15:48.250 --> 01:15:51.250
And so you should not take
anything that I say or that study

01:15:51.250 --> 01:15:53.060
to mean that you can just
take this stuff willy-nilly

01:15:53.060 --> 01:15:56.030
or at any concentration
of course, or dose.

01:15:56.030 --> 01:15:59.310
You always want to pay attention
to what the science says.

01:15:59.310 --> 01:16:02.040
That paper fortunately is
freely available online.

01:16:02.040 --> 01:16:04.270
And we will also provide
a link to that study.

01:16:04.270 --> 01:16:06.140
For those of you that
are interested in SAMe

01:16:06.140 --> 01:16:10.170
and its usage for the treatment
of various types of pain,

01:16:10.170 --> 01:16:11.873
and perhaps other benefits,

01:16:12.720 --> 01:16:16.017
a number of companies
have stopped making SAMe

01:16:16.017 --> 01:16:18.930
instead what they're now
focusing on is what they think

01:16:18.930 --> 01:16:22.265
is a better or more
bioavailable alternative,

01:16:22.265 --> 01:16:27.070
which is 5-methyltetrahydrofolate
or 5-MTHF.

01:16:30.170 --> 01:16:33.550
This molecule is necessary
for converting homocysteine

01:16:33.550 --> 01:16:37.320
to methionine, which is
then converted to SAMe

01:16:37.320 --> 01:16:40.600
so rather than taking SAMe directly,

01:16:40.600 --> 01:16:42.580
the idea is to take
something that's upstream

01:16:42.580 --> 01:16:46.570
of SAMe and make more SAMe
endogenously available.

01:16:46.570 --> 01:16:48.010
This is a different strategy.

01:16:48.010 --> 01:16:49.880
I've talked about this strategy before

01:16:49.880 --> 01:16:53.270
for increasing other things
like growth hormone, et cetera.

01:16:53.270 --> 01:16:55.430
There's always this
question of whether or not

01:16:55.430 --> 01:16:58.070
in trying to increase the
amount of a particular molecule

01:16:58.070 --> 01:17:00.257
in the body, whether or not
taking that specific molecule

01:17:00.257 --> 01:17:03.630
was the best thing or
working further upstream

01:17:03.630 --> 01:17:07.260
as it's referred to
working on the precursor

01:17:07.260 --> 01:17:09.070
or increasing the levels of the precursor

01:17:09.070 --> 01:17:10.990
is the better way to go.

01:17:10.990 --> 01:17:15.990
It appears that this
5-MTHF is the strategy

01:17:16.160 --> 01:17:21.160
that people are now taking in
place of taking SAMe directly.

01:17:21.220 --> 01:17:22.390
So in other words, they're taking this

01:17:22.390 --> 01:17:25.430
in order to get elevated levels of SAMe.

01:17:25.430 --> 01:17:26.840
Now, I'd like to turn our attention

01:17:26.840 --> 01:17:31.570
to a completely non drug, non
supplement related approach

01:17:31.570 --> 01:17:32.960
to dealing with pain.

01:17:32.960 --> 01:17:36.960
And it's one that has existed
for thousands of years.

01:17:36.960 --> 01:17:40.864
And that only recently has the
Western scientific community

01:17:40.864 --> 01:17:43.820
started to pay serious attention to,

01:17:43.820 --> 01:17:46.850
but they have started to
pay serious attention to it.

01:17:46.850 --> 01:17:51.680
And there is terrific mechanistic
science to now explain

01:17:51.680 --> 01:17:55.600
how and why acupuncture can work very well

01:17:55.600 --> 01:17:58.090
for the treatment of
certain forms of pain.

01:17:58.090 --> 01:18:01.590
Now, first off, I want to
tell you what was told to me

01:18:01.590 --> 01:18:04.490
by our director or Chief
of the Pain Division

01:18:04.490 --> 01:18:07.010
at Stanford School of
Medicine, Dr. Sean Mackey,

01:18:07.010 --> 01:18:10.240
which was that some
people respond very well

01:18:10.240 --> 01:18:13.246
to acupuncture and others do not.

01:18:13.246 --> 01:18:17.470
And the challenge is
identifying who'll respond well

01:18:17.470 --> 01:18:19.760
and who won't respond well.

01:18:19.760 --> 01:18:21.280
Now, when I say won't respond well,

01:18:21.280 --> 01:18:23.438
that doesn't necessarily
mean that they responded

01:18:23.438 --> 01:18:26.500
in a negative way, that
it was bad for them,

01:18:26.500 --> 01:18:29.890
but it does appear that
a fraction of people

01:18:29.890 --> 01:18:33.020
experienced tremendous pain
relief from acupuncture

01:18:33.020 --> 01:18:35.900
and others experience
none at all or very little

01:18:35.900 --> 01:18:37.410
to the point where they have to seek out

01:18:37.410 --> 01:18:38.673
other forms of treatment.

01:18:39.830 --> 01:18:42.670
The science on this is still ongoing.

01:18:42.670 --> 01:18:44.640
There was actually an excellent
paper published on this

01:18:44.640 --> 01:18:47.050
in the Journal of the
American Medical Association,

01:18:47.050 --> 01:18:50.620
one of the premier
medical clinical journals.

01:18:50.620 --> 01:18:52.780
And it basically reinforced the idea

01:18:52.780 --> 01:18:55.629
that you have responders
and non-responders.

01:18:55.629 --> 01:18:59.040
A number of laboratories
have started to explore

01:18:59.040 --> 01:19:01.250
how acupuncture works.

01:19:01.250 --> 01:19:03.750
And one of the premier
laboratories for this

01:19:03.750 --> 01:19:07.624
is Qiufu Ma's lab at
Harvard Medical School.

01:19:07.624 --> 01:19:11.480
Qiufu has spent many years
studying the pain system

01:19:11.480 --> 01:19:13.950
and a system that's
related to the pain system,

01:19:13.950 --> 01:19:17.603
which is the system that
controls our sensation of itch.

01:19:18.860 --> 01:19:21.230
Just as a brief aside about itch,

01:19:21.230 --> 01:19:25.470
itch and pain are often co
associated with one another.

01:19:25.470 --> 01:19:27.650
I was recently in Texas,
and I will tell you,

01:19:27.650 --> 01:19:30.000
they have some mean mosquitoes.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:32.590
They're small, but
whatever they're injecting

01:19:32.590 --> 01:19:33.550
into your skin.

01:19:33.550 --> 01:19:35.740
Well, here I am talking now
about my subjective experience

01:19:35.740 --> 01:19:38.030
of pain, whatever they
injected into my skin

01:19:38.030 --> 01:19:42.230
felt to me like the most
extreme mosquito bites

01:19:42.230 --> 01:19:44.830
I've ever had, not while
they were biting me,

01:19:44.830 --> 01:19:47.390
not while they were
injecting the venom, but boy,

01:19:47.390 --> 01:19:50.271
those Texas mosquitoes make me itch.

01:19:50.271 --> 01:19:51.400
How do they do it?

01:19:51.400 --> 01:19:55.540
Well, their venom creates little packets

01:19:55.540 --> 01:19:58.430
of so-called histamine that travel around

01:19:58.430 --> 01:20:01.070
those packets are called mast cells,

01:20:01.070 --> 01:20:03.400
little packets of histamine
that go to that location

01:20:03.400 --> 01:20:05.640
and make me and presumably you

01:20:05.640 --> 01:20:07.860
want to scratch those mosquito bites.

01:20:07.860 --> 01:20:09.080
I scratch mine you scratch yours,

01:20:09.080 --> 01:20:11.050
but we both scratch our mosquito bites.

01:20:11.050 --> 01:20:13.140
And when we do that, the
histamines are released.

01:20:13.140 --> 01:20:16.510
That gets red and inflamed
and the itch even worse.

01:20:16.510 --> 01:20:19.230
The inflammation is actually
caused by the histamine.

01:20:19.230 --> 01:20:24.230
Well, that experience of
inflammation and pain and itch

01:20:25.810 --> 01:20:26.643
is what we call a pyrogenic experience.

01:20:26.643 --> 01:20:29.910
So we we have pain which is
nociception, essentially,

01:20:29.910 --> 01:20:34.672
I know that the pain of aficionado

01:20:34.672 --> 01:20:36.830
always get a little upset
because they say, oh,

01:20:36.830 --> 01:20:38.730
there's no such thing
as as a pain receptor,

01:20:38.730 --> 01:20:40.160
it's no susceptive receptors

01:20:40.160 --> 01:20:41.790
and pain is subjective experience.

01:20:41.790 --> 01:20:43.510
Yes, I acknowledge all that.

01:20:43.510 --> 01:20:46.470
But for fluency, let's
just think about pain

01:20:46.470 --> 01:20:49.100
as a certain experience and
itch as a separate experience,

01:20:49.100 --> 01:20:52.360
but they often exist together
because those mosquito bites

01:20:52.360 --> 01:20:55.940
were what I would call painful,
or at least not pleasant.

01:20:55.940 --> 01:20:58.770
They didn't just itch,
they were also painful nuts

01:20:58.770 --> 01:21:01.780
because itch brings with it inflammation

01:21:01.780 --> 01:21:04.800
and inflammation often
brings with it pain relief,

01:21:04.800 --> 01:21:07.690
but it can also bring with
it the sensation of pain.

01:21:07.690 --> 01:21:10.660
So itch and pain are
two separate phenomenon.

01:21:10.660 --> 01:21:13.860
It was actually discovered
through a really interesting

01:21:13.860 --> 01:21:15.490
phenomenon that relates to something

01:21:15.490 --> 01:21:18.290
that is actually consumed
in supplement form,

01:21:18.290 --> 01:21:20.490
which is this tropical legume.

01:21:20.490 --> 01:21:23.690
It's actually a bean
called Mucuna pruriens.

01:21:23.690 --> 01:21:28.690
That's M-U-C-U-N-A that's
one word P-R-U-I-E-N-S

01:21:29.360 --> 01:21:34.360
Mucuna pruriens is a bean,
it's as legume that this bean

01:21:34.730 --> 01:21:37.310
is 99% L-DOPA.

01:21:37.310 --> 01:21:40.060
It's dopamine or rather it's
the precursor to dopamine

01:21:40.060 --> 01:21:42.470
and people buy this stuff
and take it over the counter

01:21:42.470 --> 01:21:44.680
as ways to increase
their levels of dopamine.

01:21:44.680 --> 01:21:47.860
It does make you feel
really dopamine doubt,

01:21:47.860 --> 01:21:50.800
meaning it makes you feel a
little high and really motivated

01:21:50.800 --> 01:21:53.690
and really energetic
a lot like other drugs

01:21:53.690 --> 01:21:55.130
that will do that.

01:21:55.130 --> 01:21:57.810
I don't necessarily recommend
taking Mucuna pruriens.

01:21:57.810 --> 01:22:00.030
I personally don't like taking it.

01:22:00.030 --> 01:22:01.160
Doesn't make me feel good.

01:22:01.160 --> 01:22:03.890
I crash really hard when I take it.

01:22:03.890 --> 01:22:07.880
But on the outside of
this bean is a compound

01:22:07.880 --> 01:22:10.520
that makes people itch.

01:22:10.520 --> 01:22:12.650
So they remove this when you
take it in supplement form.

01:22:12.650 --> 01:22:14.580
In fact, it's usually in capsule form,

01:22:14.580 --> 01:22:18.080
but the outside of this
bean, it's like a hairy bean.

01:22:18.080 --> 01:22:21.056
And those little hairs contain a compound,

01:22:21.056 --> 01:22:24.840
which was actually used
to study and identify

01:22:24.840 --> 01:22:27.110
these itchy receptors in the skin.

01:22:27.110 --> 01:22:30.060
So we don't have time to go
into all the details of itch,

01:22:30.060 --> 01:22:32.420
but it's pretty interesting
that you have these compounds

01:22:32.420 --> 01:22:34.030
out in nature that can make us itch.

01:22:34.030 --> 01:22:35.560
Inside them they have dopamine.

01:22:35.560 --> 01:22:36.540
I mean, this is really weird,

01:22:36.540 --> 01:22:38.900
but plant compounds are really powerful.

01:22:38.900 --> 01:22:41.640
So don't let anyone tell
you that because something's

01:22:41.640 --> 01:22:44.052
from a plant or an earth
that it's not powerful.

01:22:44.052 --> 01:22:47.500
There are very powerful
plant and herb compounds.

01:22:47.500 --> 01:22:50.220
Mucuna prurien being one of
them with dopamine on the inside

01:22:50.220 --> 01:22:52.310
and itchy stuff on the outside.

01:22:52.310 --> 01:22:54.610
Now, what does this all
have to do with acupuncture?

01:22:54.610 --> 01:22:58.750
Well, Qiufu Ma's lab
has not just identified

01:22:58.750 --> 01:23:01.950
the itch pathway, this pruritus
genes as they're called,

01:23:01.950 --> 01:23:04.940
which causes itch and
the pyrogenic phenomenon

01:23:04.940 --> 01:23:07.230
of itch being separate from pain.

01:23:07.230 --> 01:23:12.230
His lab has also studied how
acupuncture causes relief of,

01:23:12.760 --> 01:23:16.100
but also can exacerbate pain.

01:23:16.100 --> 01:23:18.080
Now, the form of acupuncture
that they explored

01:23:18.080 --> 01:23:20.710
was one that's commonly in
use called electroacupuncture.

01:23:20.710 --> 01:23:23.100
So this isn't just putting little needles

01:23:23.100 --> 01:23:25.000
into different parts of the body.

01:23:25.000 --> 01:23:28.730
These needles are able to
pass an electrical current,

01:23:28.730 --> 01:23:29.970
not magically, but because they have

01:23:29.970 --> 01:23:31.360
a little wire going back to a device

01:23:31.360 --> 01:23:32.760
and you can pass electrical current.

01:23:32.760 --> 01:23:34.053
Here's what they found.

01:23:34.053 --> 01:23:37.450
This is a study published
in the journal neuron

01:23:37.450 --> 01:23:40.500
Cell Press journal, excellent
journal, very high stringency.

01:23:40.500 --> 01:23:43.530
So what Qiufu Ma's lab found
was that if electroacupuncture

01:23:45.000 --> 01:23:48.343
is provided to the abdomen,
to the stomach area,

01:23:49.240 --> 01:23:52.170
it creates activation of what are called

01:23:52.170 --> 01:23:53.410
the sympathetic ganglia.

01:23:53.410 --> 01:23:55.070
These have nothing to do with sympathy

01:23:55.070 --> 01:23:58.350
in the emotional sense has to
do with the stress response.

01:23:58.350 --> 01:23:59.630
Sympa just means together.

01:23:59.630 --> 01:24:02.693
So it activated a bunch of
neurons along the spinal cord.

01:24:03.680 --> 01:24:06.780
And the activation of
these neurons evolves

01:24:06.780 --> 01:24:11.780
neural adrenaline and something
called NPY neuropeptide Y.

01:24:13.000 --> 01:24:15.630
The long and short of it is
that stimulating the abdomen

01:24:15.630 --> 01:24:20.630
with electroacupuncture was
either anti-inflammatory

01:24:20.730 --> 01:24:22.650
or it could cause inflammation.

01:24:22.650 --> 01:24:25.200
It could actually exacerbate
inflammation depending

01:24:25.200 --> 01:24:28.810
on whether or not it was
of low or high intensity.

01:24:28.810 --> 01:24:31.020
Now that makes it a very
precarious technique.

01:24:31.020 --> 01:24:33.360
And this may speak to some of the reason

01:24:33.360 --> 01:24:36.320
why some people report
relief from acupuncture

01:24:36.320 --> 01:24:37.780
and others do not.

01:24:37.780 --> 01:24:41.550
However, they went a step further
and stimulated other areas

01:24:41.550 --> 01:24:43.472
of the body using electroacupuncture.

01:24:43.472 --> 01:24:46.100
And what they found is that
stimulation of the legs

01:24:46.100 --> 01:24:47.930
of the hind limbs, as
it's called an animals,

01:24:47.930 --> 01:24:51.380
and the legs in humans caused a circuit,

01:24:51.380 --> 01:24:53.450
a neural circuit to be activated that goes

01:24:53.450 --> 01:24:57.920
from the legs up to an area
of the base of the brain

01:24:57.920 --> 01:25:01.310
called the DMV not the DMH,
which I mentioned earlier,

01:25:01.310 --> 01:25:04.350
but the DMV like you go to the DMV,

01:25:04.350 --> 01:25:06.820
which is a miserable experience
for most people, forgive me,

01:25:06.820 --> 01:25:09.320
DMV employees, but let's be honest

01:25:09.320 --> 01:25:13.160
most people don't enjoy
going to the DMV as patrons,

01:25:13.160 --> 01:25:15.040
but we have to so we go.

01:25:15.040 --> 01:25:19.450
The DMV and low intensity stimulation,

01:25:19.450 --> 01:25:23.920
this electroacupuncture of the
hind limbs activated the DMV

01:25:23.920 --> 01:25:25.830
and activated the adrenal glands,

01:25:25.830 --> 01:25:30.100
which sit at top of your
kidneys and cause the release

01:25:30.100 --> 01:25:31.810
of what are called catecholamines.

01:25:31.810 --> 01:25:35.340
And those were strongly anti-inflammatory.

01:25:35.340 --> 01:25:40.340
In other words, electroacupuncture
of the legs and feet can,

01:25:40.360 --> 01:25:43.100
if done correctly, be anti-inflammatory

01:25:43.100 --> 01:25:45.140
and reduce symptoms of pain.

01:25:45.140 --> 01:25:48.430
And can we think accelerate wound healing

01:25:48.430 --> 01:25:51.900
because activations of these
catecholaminergic pathways

01:25:51.900 --> 01:25:54.140
can accelerate wound healing as well.

01:25:54.140 --> 01:25:58.350
So the takeaway from this is
that while there are thousands

01:25:58.350 --> 01:26:02.860
of years and millions of
subjects involved in explorations

01:26:02.860 --> 01:26:04.813
of electroacupuncture and acupuncture,

01:26:06.370 --> 01:26:09.030
Western medicine is
starting to come into this

01:26:09.030 --> 01:26:11.080
and start to explore underlying mechanism.

01:26:11.080 --> 01:26:13.720
Now, for those of you
that love acupuncture

01:26:13.720 --> 01:26:16.300
and are real proponents of it,

01:26:16.300 --> 01:26:17.640
it's worked for you, you might say,

01:26:17.640 --> 01:26:20.330
well, why does Western medicine
even need to come into this?

01:26:20.330 --> 01:26:22.370
Why should they even be exploring this?

01:26:22.370 --> 01:26:24.400
But we should all be
relieved that they are

01:26:24.400 --> 01:26:26.880
because what's starting to happen now

01:26:26.880 --> 01:26:29.540
is that as the mechanistic basis for this

01:26:29.540 --> 01:26:31.563
is starting to come to light,

01:26:32.570 --> 01:26:35.990
insurance coverage of
things like acupuncture

01:26:35.990 --> 01:26:38.150
is starting to emerge as well.

01:26:38.150 --> 01:26:40.380
And this is in contrast to other therapies

01:26:40.380 --> 01:26:43.000
for which there's a lot
of anecdotal evidence,

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:45.180
but very little mechanistic understanding.

01:26:45.180 --> 01:26:48.407
One example of that would
be laser photo biomodulation

01:26:48.407 --> 01:26:52.410
the use of lasers of
different types really

01:26:52.410 --> 01:26:54.680
to treat pain and to
accelerate wound healing.

01:26:54.680 --> 01:26:57.590
A lot of people claim that
this can really help them.

01:26:57.590 --> 01:27:00.129
However, most places,
at least in the States,

01:27:00.129 --> 01:27:01.800
won't cover this with insurance

01:27:01.800 --> 01:27:04.184
or don't perform this in standard clinics.

01:27:04.184 --> 01:27:08.310
And the reason is the underlying
mechanism isn't known.

01:27:08.310 --> 01:27:10.900
I'm not going to get into the
argument about whether or not

01:27:10.900 --> 01:27:14.660
mechanistic understanding
should or should not be required

01:27:14.660 --> 01:27:17.800
in order to have insurance
coverage of things that work.

01:27:17.800 --> 01:27:19.110
That's not what this is about.

01:27:19.110 --> 01:27:21.350
And that actually will
be a boring discussion

01:27:21.350 --> 01:27:23.670
because I'm shouting at
a tunnel through you.

01:27:23.670 --> 01:27:25.330
And I wouldn't be able
to hear you shout back

01:27:25.330 --> 01:27:27.220
no matter what your stance on that is,

01:27:27.220 --> 01:27:30.938
but just trust me when I
say that I am both relieved

01:27:30.938 --> 01:27:35.040
and delighted to hear that
excellent medical institutions

01:27:35.040 --> 01:27:39.033
like Stanford are starting to
think about electroacupuncture

01:27:39.033 --> 01:27:39.866
and how it can work.

01:27:39.866 --> 01:27:42.210
That places like Harvard
Medical School are starting

01:27:42.210 --> 01:27:44.320
to explore this at a mechanistic level.

01:27:44.320 --> 01:27:46.840
And I do believe that
there's an open-mindedness

01:27:46.840 --> 01:27:49.402
that starting to emerge for instance,

01:27:49.402 --> 01:27:52.000
the National Institutes of Health,

01:27:52.000 --> 01:27:54.090
not only has an institute
for mental health

01:27:54.090 --> 01:27:55.760
and cancer research and an eye institute,

01:27:55.760 --> 01:27:58.553
but now complementary
health, the so-called NCCIH.

01:27:59.700 --> 01:28:01.970
National Institutes of
Complementary Health

01:28:01.970 --> 01:28:04.660
that is exploring things
like electroacupuncture,

01:28:04.660 --> 01:28:08.080
meditation, various supplements
and things of those sort.

01:28:08.080 --> 01:28:10.190
I do think that we're entering
a new realm in which things

01:28:10.190 --> 01:28:13.800
like pain and pain management
will be met with more openness

01:28:13.800 --> 01:28:15.970
by all physicians, at
least that's my hope.

01:28:15.970 --> 01:28:18.829
So please take that into
consideration right now.

01:28:18.829 --> 01:28:22.270
The mechanistic evidence
for laser photobiomodulation

01:28:22.270 --> 01:28:23.190
is not strong.

01:28:23.190 --> 01:28:27.330
One of the major issues
or the barriers to that

01:28:27.330 --> 01:28:30.235
is that most of the
studies that are out there

01:28:30.235 --> 01:28:33.030
were actually paid for by companies

01:28:33.030 --> 01:28:38.030
that build devices for
laser photobiomodulation.

01:28:38.180 --> 01:28:40.800
And so we really need
independent studies funded

01:28:40.800 --> 01:28:43.260
by federal institutions that have no bias

01:28:43.260 --> 01:28:46.900
or financial relationship
in order to gain trust

01:28:46.900 --> 01:28:48.783
in whatever data happen to emerge.

01:28:49.970 --> 01:28:51.650
There is a technique that at one time

01:28:51.650 --> 01:28:53.070
was considered alternative,

01:28:53.070 --> 01:28:55.880
but now has a lot of mechanistic science

01:28:55.880 --> 01:28:59.230
to explain how it works,
and it does indeed work

01:28:59.230 --> 01:29:03.543
for the treatment of chronic
and also for acute pain.

01:29:03.543 --> 01:29:08.543
And that treatment is hypnosis
in particular self-hypnosis.

01:29:08.550 --> 01:29:12.170
Now, my colleague at Stanford
in fact, my collaborator,

01:29:12.170 --> 01:29:14.950
Dr. David Spiegel, our
Associate Chair of Psychiatry

01:29:14.950 --> 01:29:16.670
has devoted his professional life

01:29:16.670 --> 01:29:20.300
to developing hypnosis
tools that people can use

01:29:20.300 --> 01:29:22.500
to help them sleep better, focus better,

01:29:22.500 --> 01:29:24.730
stay motivated, et cetera.

01:29:24.730 --> 01:29:26.680
While most people hear
hypnosis and they think,

01:29:26.680 --> 01:29:28.090
oh, this is stage hypnosis.

01:29:28.090 --> 01:29:29.480
People walking around like chickens

01:29:29.480 --> 01:29:30.690
are being forced to laugh

01:29:30.690 --> 01:29:33.100
or fall asleep on command, et cetera.

01:29:33.100 --> 01:29:34.620
This is completely
different than all that.

01:29:34.620 --> 01:29:37.910
This is self hypnosis
and there are now dozens,

01:29:37.910 --> 01:29:41.690
if not more quality peer
reviewed studies published

01:29:41.690 --> 01:29:44.980
in excellent journals done by Dr. Spiegel

01:29:44.980 --> 01:29:47.570
and others at other universities.

01:29:47.570 --> 01:29:50.640
It really all has to do
with how self-hypnosis

01:29:50.640 --> 01:29:54.600
can modulate activity
of the prefrontal cortex

01:29:54.600 --> 01:29:57.230
and related structures like the insula.

01:29:57.230 --> 01:30:02.230
The prefrontal cortex is involved
in our executive function

01:30:02.320 --> 01:30:04.320
as it's called, our planning,
our decision making,

01:30:04.320 --> 01:30:07.200
but also how we interpret context,

01:30:07.200 --> 01:30:10.150
what the meaning of a given sensation is.

01:30:10.150 --> 01:30:11.727
And that's extremely powerful.

01:30:11.727 --> 01:30:15.000
I just want to remind
everybody that the currency

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:17.010
of the brain and body has not changed

01:30:17.010 --> 01:30:18.690
in hundreds of thousands of years.

01:30:18.690 --> 01:30:21.010
It's always been dopamine,
serotonin, glutamate,

01:30:21.010 --> 01:30:23.350
GABA, testosterone, estrogen.

01:30:23.350 --> 01:30:25.600
What's changed are the contingencies,

01:30:25.600 --> 01:30:28.050
the events in the world
that drive whether or not

01:30:28.050 --> 01:30:31.110
we get an increase or decrease
in testosterone or estrogen,

01:30:31.110 --> 01:30:33.440
the events in the world
that dictate whether or not

01:30:33.440 --> 01:30:36.050
we get an increase or
a decrease in dopamine.

01:30:36.050 --> 01:30:38.760
Believe me, the events
that drove those increases

01:30:38.760 --> 01:30:41.090
and decreases were very
different even a 100 years ago

01:30:41.090 --> 01:30:42.470
than they are now.

01:30:42.470 --> 01:30:45.910
And as we create new things and
societies change, et cetera,

01:30:45.910 --> 01:30:50.430
they will continue to exchange information

01:30:50.430 --> 01:30:53.010
in the same currency, which
is dopamine, serotonin,

01:30:53.010 --> 01:30:55.450
and all these other
neuromodulators and chemicals.

01:30:55.450 --> 01:30:57.629
Hypnosis takes advantage of this

01:30:57.629 --> 01:31:02.040
by allowing an individual,
you, if you like

01:31:02.040 --> 01:31:04.610
to change the way that you
interpret particular events

01:31:04.610 --> 01:31:06.990
and to actually experience
what would be painful

01:31:06.990 --> 01:31:09.180
as less painful or not painful.

01:31:09.180 --> 01:31:10.540
And that's just the example of pain.

01:31:10.540 --> 01:31:12.900
Hypnosis is powerful
for other reasons too.

01:31:12.900 --> 01:31:15.680
It actually can help
rewire neural circuits

01:31:15.680 --> 01:31:18.160
so that you don't experience as much pain

01:31:18.160 --> 01:31:20.210
so that you can sleep
faster, focus faster.

01:31:20.210 --> 01:31:23.520
If this is all sounding very fantastical

01:31:23.520 --> 01:31:26.113
well, it's supported by data.

01:31:27.000 --> 01:31:30.070
The data are that when
people do self-hypnosis

01:31:30.070 --> 01:31:33.260
even brief self-hypnosis
of 10 or 15 minutes,

01:31:33.260 --> 01:31:36.670
a few times a week, maybe
even returned to that hypnosis

01:31:36.670 --> 01:31:39.370
by just using a one minute a day hypnosis,

01:31:39.370 --> 01:31:43.380
they can achieve significant
and often very impressive

01:31:43.380 --> 01:31:46.210
degrees of pain relief in chronic pain

01:31:46.210 --> 01:31:47.760
whether or not that chronic pain arises

01:31:47.760 --> 01:31:50.660
through things like fibromyalgia
or through other sources.

01:31:50.660 --> 01:31:52.150
If you want to check this out,

01:31:52.150 --> 01:31:54.190
there's a wonderful zero cost resource

01:31:54.190 --> 01:31:56.240
that's grounded in this work.

01:31:56.240 --> 01:31:58.200
It's the app reveri.com.

01:31:59.780 --> 01:32:03.198
So R-E-V-E-R-I.com.

01:32:03.198 --> 01:32:05.980
There you can download a zero cost app

01:32:07.020 --> 01:32:10.340
for Apple phones or for Android phones.

01:32:10.340 --> 01:32:12.680
And there are a variety of
different hypnosis scripts.

01:32:12.680 --> 01:32:14.280
These are actually self hypnosis scripts,

01:32:14.280 --> 01:32:17.170
and you'll actually hear Dr.
David Spiegel talking to you.

01:32:17.170 --> 01:32:19.680
He can teach you about
hypnosis and how it works.

01:32:19.680 --> 01:32:21.468
There are links to scientific studies

01:32:21.468 --> 01:32:24.930
that web address that I
gave you before reveri.com.

01:32:24.930 --> 01:32:27.290
You can see the various studies
and the various write-ups

01:32:27.290 --> 01:32:29.560
related to those studies
and how this all works.

01:32:29.560 --> 01:32:30.926
And they're simple protocols.

01:32:30.926 --> 01:32:33.790
You just click on a tab and
you listen to the self-hypnosis

01:32:33.790 --> 01:32:36.180
and it will take you into hypnosis.

01:32:36.180 --> 01:32:39.370
And several of those hypnosis
grips have been shown

01:32:39.370 --> 01:32:44.240
clinically to relieve certain
patterns of chronic pain.

01:32:44.240 --> 01:32:46.630
So it's a powerful tool,
and I encourage you not

01:32:46.630 --> 01:32:50.010
to write off the non-drug
non supplement tools

01:32:50.010 --> 01:32:53.270
as less than powerful
because indeed many people

01:32:53.270 --> 01:32:55.290
experience tremendous relief from them.

01:32:55.290 --> 01:32:57.850
And of course, they also can be combined

01:32:57.850 --> 01:33:00.170
with drug treatments
if that's right for you

01:33:00.170 --> 01:33:03.240
or with supplements and things
of that sort to treat pain,

01:33:03.240 --> 01:33:04.720
if that's right for you.

01:33:04.720 --> 01:33:08.890
So again, electroacupuncture
now often supported

01:33:08.890 --> 01:33:11.220
by insurance, not always, but often.

01:33:11.220 --> 01:33:13.890
Great mechanistic data starting to emerge.

01:33:13.890 --> 01:33:17.320
Hypnosis, terrific tool.

01:33:17.320 --> 01:33:19.970
There's even the self-hypnosis
tool that one can access

01:33:19.970 --> 01:33:21.980
through the zero cost app Reveri

01:33:21.980 --> 01:33:24.960
and lots of great clinical data

01:33:24.960 --> 01:33:26.680
and scientific mechanistic data.

01:33:26.680 --> 01:33:28.160
There are neuro imaging studies showing

01:33:28.160 --> 01:33:30.237
that different brain areas
are activated in hypnosis

01:33:30.237 --> 01:33:32.370
the so-called default network,

01:33:32.370 --> 01:33:35.210
kind of where your brains is kind of idols

01:33:35.210 --> 01:33:38.020
and the different circuits
that are active in at rest

01:33:38.020 --> 01:33:40.250
shift with hypnosis and shift long-term

01:33:40.250 --> 01:33:42.380
in ways that positively conserve you.

01:33:42.380 --> 01:33:45.240
And then these things like
laser photobiomodulation

01:33:45.240 --> 01:33:48.710
still more or less in that
experimental medical community.

01:33:48.710 --> 01:33:51.380
I should say, Western Medical
Community, not so certain,

01:33:51.380 --> 01:33:53.570
but hopefully there will be data soon,

01:33:53.570 --> 01:33:55.960
and hopefully those data
will point to mechanisms

01:33:55.960 --> 01:33:58.410
that allow the insurance companies

01:33:58.410 --> 01:34:03.350
and other sort of medical
bodies to support them

01:34:03.350 --> 01:34:06.090
if indeed they have a mechanistic basis.

01:34:06.090 --> 01:34:09.430
I just want to briefly touch on
a common method of pain relief

01:34:09.430 --> 01:34:12.180
that speaks to a more general principle

01:34:12.180 --> 01:34:14.440
of how things like electroacupuncture,

01:34:14.440 --> 01:34:17.160
and also some of these
new emerging techniques

01:34:17.160 --> 01:34:20.020
of kind of like active tissue release

01:34:20.020 --> 01:34:21.870
and this principle that
you hear a lot about

01:34:21.870 --> 01:34:24.210
in sports medicine now that
when you have pain or injury

01:34:24.210 --> 01:34:26.680
at one site, that you
should provide pressure

01:34:26.680 --> 01:34:28.030
above and below that site.

01:34:28.030 --> 01:34:31.810
You may have seen this in the
Olympics, which is ongoing now

01:34:31.810 --> 01:34:34.720
where people will put tape on their body

01:34:34.720 --> 01:34:36.509
at certain locations oftentimes.

01:34:36.509 --> 01:34:39.960
The logic or what they're
saying is that this is designed

01:34:39.960 --> 01:34:43.240
to create relief in a joint or in a limb

01:34:43.240 --> 01:34:46.920
that's below the tape, not
necessarily under the tape,

01:34:46.920 --> 01:34:48.220
but above or below.

01:34:48.220 --> 01:34:50.060
So for instance, if there's
pain in one shoulder,

01:34:50.060 --> 01:34:53.040
sometimes we'll put it
on the trapezius muscle

01:34:53.040 --> 01:34:53.873
or things of that sort.

01:34:53.873 --> 01:34:56.030
It turns out that there
is a basis for this

01:34:56.030 --> 01:34:58.730
because of the way that
these different nerves run in

01:34:58.730 --> 01:35:02.680
from the skin and from the
muscles up into the spinal cord

01:35:02.680 --> 01:35:05.330
and into the brainstem providing pressure

01:35:05.330 --> 01:35:07.960
on one nerve pathway can
often impact another pathway.

01:35:07.960 --> 01:35:10.810
And the simplest and most
common example of this is one

01:35:10.810 --> 01:35:13.020
that we all do
instinctually or intuitively

01:35:13.020 --> 01:35:14.820
even animals do this.

01:35:14.820 --> 01:35:17.740
This is something that in the
textbooks is all is called

01:35:17.740 --> 01:35:20.610
the Gate Theory of Pain
developed by Melzack and Wall

01:35:20.610 --> 01:35:22.370
kind of classic theory.

01:35:22.370 --> 01:35:26.000
Basically we have receptors in our skin,

01:35:26.000 --> 01:35:28.370
the so-called C fibers, that's just a name

01:35:28.370 --> 01:35:30.250
for these little wires that come

01:35:30.250 --> 01:35:33.840
from a particular class
of DRGs that's very thin

01:35:33.840 --> 01:35:35.840
that brings about certain kinds

01:35:35.840 --> 01:35:37.500
of nasal scepter information.

01:35:37.500 --> 01:35:38.840
I want to say pain information,

01:35:38.840 --> 01:35:42.230
but then the pain people believe
are not their pain people.

01:35:42.230 --> 01:35:44.500
Sometimes they're a pain
because what they tell me

01:35:44.500 --> 01:35:46.900
is they're on pain
receptors okay, nociceptors

01:35:46.900 --> 01:35:50.360
That information comes in C fibers

01:35:50.360 --> 01:35:53.940
and what happens when we injure something

01:35:53.940 --> 01:35:57.370
well, provided that we won't
damage it worse by touching it,

01:35:57.370 --> 01:36:01.420
oftentimes what we will do is
we will rub the source of pain

01:36:01.420 --> 01:36:05.470
or the location in which
we were experiencing pain.

01:36:05.470 --> 01:36:10.470
And it turns out that's not
an unuseful thing to do.

01:36:10.550 --> 01:36:14.380
When we rub our skin or an area,

01:36:14.380 --> 01:36:16.550
or we provide pressure nearby it,

01:36:16.550 --> 01:36:18.380
we activate the so-called A fibers,

01:36:18.380 --> 01:36:22.120
the bigger wires and
neurons that innovate,

01:36:22.120 --> 01:36:24.550
meaning they jut into that area of skin.

01:36:24.550 --> 01:36:27.470
And those A fibers, the ones that respond

01:36:27.470 --> 01:36:31.210
to mechanical pressure
actually are able to inhibit

01:36:31.210 --> 01:36:33.310
those C fibers, the ones that are carrying

01:36:33.310 --> 01:36:35.170
that so-called pain information.

01:36:35.170 --> 01:36:38.920
So rubbing an area or providing
pressure above or below

01:36:38.920 --> 01:36:42.990
an injury actually provides
real pain relief support

01:36:42.990 --> 01:36:46.770
for the location of
that injury or that pain

01:36:46.770 --> 01:36:49.070
because of the way that
these different patterns

01:36:49.070 --> 01:36:51.600
or these different types
of neurons interact

01:36:51.600 --> 01:36:52.500
with one another.

01:36:52.500 --> 01:36:53.810
And when I say it inhibits it,

01:36:53.810 --> 01:36:55.493
I don't mean that it like shouts at it,

01:36:55.493 --> 01:36:58.340
what it does is it releases
it's literally kind of

01:36:58.340 --> 01:37:01.340
like vomits up a little
bit of a neurotransmitter

01:37:01.340 --> 01:37:02.280
called GABA.

01:37:02.280 --> 01:37:04.960
And GABA is a
neurotransmitter that inhibits

01:37:04.960 --> 01:37:08.210
it quiets the activity of other neurons.

01:37:08.210 --> 01:37:11.890
And so it's acting as kind
of an analgesic, if you will,

01:37:11.890 --> 01:37:15.690
it's acting as its own
form of drug that you make

01:37:15.690 --> 01:37:19.090
with your body to quiet the
activity of these pain neurons.

01:37:19.090 --> 01:37:21.300
So rubbing a wound
provided it doesn't damage

01:37:21.300 --> 01:37:25.340
the wound worse or providing
pressure above or below

01:37:25.340 --> 01:37:28.290
typically it's above a particular injury

01:37:28.290 --> 01:37:30.760
can have a real effect in
relieving some of the pain

01:37:30.760 --> 01:37:31.593
of that injury.

01:37:31.593 --> 01:37:34.060
And some people have speculated
this as through fascia,

01:37:34.060 --> 01:37:37.000
or this is through other
bodily organs and tissues.

01:37:37.000 --> 01:37:39.360
And it might be we're going to
do a whole episode on fascia.

01:37:39.360 --> 01:37:41.150
It's extremely interesting tissue,

01:37:41.150 --> 01:37:43.140
but right now it seems
that the main source

01:37:43.140 --> 01:37:47.460
of that pain relief is through
this A fiber inhibition

01:37:47.460 --> 01:37:50.840
of these C fibers
so-called Melzack and Wall

01:37:50.840 --> 01:37:53.020
Gate Theory of Pain if
you'd like to look it up

01:37:53.020 --> 01:37:55.170
and learn about that further.

01:37:55.170 --> 01:37:56.950
Now, let's talk about a phenomenon

01:37:56.950 --> 01:38:00.080
that has long intrigued
and perplexed people

01:38:00.080 --> 01:38:02.610
for probably thousands of years.

01:38:02.610 --> 01:38:05.190
And that's redheads.

01:38:05.190 --> 01:38:07.760
You may have heard before that
redheads have a higher pain

01:38:07.760 --> 01:38:10.060
threshold than other individuals.

01:38:10.060 --> 01:38:12.271
And indeed, that is true.

01:38:12.271 --> 01:38:16.090
There's now a study that
looked at this mechanistically.

01:38:16.090 --> 01:38:20.600
There's a gene called the MC1R gene.

01:38:20.600 --> 01:38:22.990
And this MC1R gene encodes

01:38:22.990 --> 01:38:25.470
for a number of different proteins.

01:38:25.470 --> 01:38:27.780
Some of those proteins
of course are related

01:38:27.780 --> 01:38:29.360
to the production of melanin.

01:38:29.360 --> 01:38:31.680
This is why redheads often not always,

01:38:31.680 --> 01:38:33.750
but often are very fair skinned.

01:38:33.750 --> 01:38:35.850
Sometimes have freckles, not always.

01:38:35.850 --> 01:38:37.510
And of course have red hair.

01:38:37.510 --> 01:38:40.100
Some people are really intense ginger's

01:38:40.100 --> 01:38:43.840
not psychologically or emotionally
intense perhaps that too,

01:38:43.840 --> 01:38:46.140
but meaning their hair is very, very red.

01:38:46.140 --> 01:38:47.460
Others, it's a lighter red.

01:38:47.460 --> 01:38:50.590
So of course there's
variation here, but this gene,

01:38:50.590 --> 01:38:55.590
this MC1R gene is associated
with a pathway that relates

01:38:56.200 --> 01:38:58.880
to something that I've talked
about on this podcast before

01:38:58.880 --> 01:39:03.880
during the episode on hunger
and feeding and this is POMC.

01:39:04.300 --> 01:39:08.500
POMC stands for pro-opiomelanocortin

01:39:08.500 --> 01:39:11.240
and POMC is cut up.

01:39:11.240 --> 01:39:13.420
It's cleaved into different hormones,

01:39:13.420 --> 01:39:16.720
including one that
enhances pain perception.

01:39:16.720 --> 01:39:19.360
This is melanocyte stimulating hormone.

01:39:19.360 --> 01:39:23.150
And another one that
blocks pain beta endorphin.

01:39:23.150 --> 01:39:25.760
Now, if you listen to the
episodes on testosterone

01:39:25.760 --> 01:39:29.300
and estrogen and the episodes
on hunger and feeding,

01:39:29.300 --> 01:39:32.230
some of these molecules
will start to ring a bell.

01:39:32.230 --> 01:39:34.520
Things like melano
stimulating hormone relate

01:39:34.520 --> 01:39:35.970
to pigmentation of the skin

01:39:35.970 --> 01:39:38.240
relate to sexual arousal, et cetera,

01:39:38.240 --> 01:39:40.333
but it turns out that in red heads,

